songs.comment_text: I met Philip Glass when I first arrived in NYC, after having lived abroad for 7 years in Central Europe.  In fact, it was very odd meeting.  I had been given a comp ticket to attend a "kiddie concert" at Carnegie Hall, I don't remember what orchestra was playing, and it featured the music of Philip Glass.  So I had a great seat, in fact, a box seat in one of those side boxes looking right out over the stage.  And I'm sitting there in the morning before the concert is about to begin, and who should sit down behind me, but Philip Glass along with his wife.  At the end of the concert, attended by all those school kids, I got up and I turned and said to Mr. Glass, "My father ( member of the percussion section of the Baltimore Symphony Orchestra) is a great fan of your work, Einstein on the Beach.  I would like to buy him the cd of the opera, but there are two versions, the original version from 1976 and the updated later version.  Which do you recommend?"  And he said, "I personally prefer the original version from '76."  And he put his hand on my shoulder when he said that.  And I thought, Glass is not at all like his image makes him, somewhat cool, austere, he's actually a very warm person when you meet him in person.  I've also met John Cage in person, and spent an afternoon talking to him and playing chess with him, while his cat, Skookum, jumped on the chess board every now and then (and never knocked over a piece amazingly), and the same could be said of John Cage, very friendly warm person, but unlike Glass, Cage was much more impersonal.
